                    "company": "Willem Bruls",
                    "description": "Freelance dramaturge and author on music, theatre, opera and dance. He wrote a study on Wagner\u2019s Ring-cycle, on Orientalism in Opera, on Opera in Venice, and on the music of Aleppo. In 2009 his collected essays on music and theatre were published. As a music journalist he contributed to newspapers as Opernwelt, De Standaard (Belgium) and The Wall Street Journal Europe. \n\nAs a production dramaturge he worked on Il re pastore, The Abduction from the Seraglio (Antwerp), Partenope (Vienna), La Juive, Orlando furioso, M\u00e9d\u00e9e and Tristan und Isolde (Paris), Cavalli's Xerse (Lille), Tosca, Pique Dame (Riga), Werther (Erfurt), Prince Igor (Essen), Carmen, La damnation de Faust, A Little Night Music, The Rape of Lucretia, La voix humaine/L\u2019heure espagnol, Orph\u00e9e, A Midsummer Night's Dream, Een lied voor de maan, Het Lijflied, Het meisje\u2026\n\nHe realised adaptations of Romeo and Juliet for Scottish Ballet, and of Sh\u00e9h\u00e9razade and The Tempest in Amsterdam, with visual artist Shirin Neshat. With Kim Brandstrup he worked on the dance performance Life is a Dream for Rambert Ballet. For the Ruhrtriennale and Toneelgroep Amsterdam he made a stage adaptation of Pasolini\u2019s Teorema, directed by Ivo van Hove, which was selected for the Lincoln Center Festival in New York.\n\nHe also worked as a dramaturge for the Operadagen Rotterdam Festival. For the 2010 edition he directed 'Alla turca - East meets West'. For Delft Chamber Music Festival and Rotterdam Philharmonic Festival he directed 'Begin van een onbekend tijdperk' and in 2021 'Nevski Prospekt'. In 2022 he directed Sound and Fury/Erasmus with Cappella Pratensis.\n\nHe wrote the libretto Alp Arslan for composer Richard van Schoor, and together with composer Mathilde Wantenaar a libretto for the youth opera Een lied voor de Maan and for Dear Professor Einstein. Bruls conducted workshops for contemporary music theatre, libretto writing, youth opera and cultural journalism in Barcelona, Stavanger, Hobart, Ghent, Brussels and Aix-en-Provence.",
                    "title": "Author-Dramaturge",
                    "employment_type": "Self-employed"
                }
            ]
        },
